Yes, absolutely—you don't need the `$MOUNTPOINT` variable at all if you prefer. Just inline the `docker volume inspect` command directly in your `cp` statements. It evaluates the path on the fly each time, so it's efficient and avoids variable scoping issues.

### Updated Copy Commands (Inline Version)
Assuming `$VOLUME_NAME` is set (e.g., to `hub_cert-volume`) or replace it inline too:

#### Backup First (if not done):
```
sudo cp "$(docker volume inspect $VOLUME_NAME --format '{{ .Mountpoint }}')/ca.pem" "$(docker volume inspect $VOLUME_NAME --format '{{ .Mountpoint }}')/ca.pem.bak"
sudo cp "$(docker volume inspect $VOLUME_NAME --format '{{ .Mountpoint }}')/ca-key.pem" "$(docker volume inspect $VOLUME_NAME --format '{{ .Mountpoint }}')/ca-key.pem.bak"
```

#### Copy New Certs:
```
sudo cp new_ca.crt "$(docker volume inspect $VOLUME_NAME --format '{{ .Mountpoint }}')/ca.pem"
sudo cp new_ca.key "$(docker volume inspect $VOLUME_NAME --format '{{ .Mountpoint }}')/ca-key.pem"
```

- The `$(...)` runs the inspect command and substitutes the path (e.g., `/var/lib/docker/volumes/hub_cert-volume/_data`) right into the `cp` target.
- Verify as before: `sudo openssl x509 -in "$(docker volume inspect $VOLUME_NAME --format '{{ .Mountpoint }}')/ca.pem" -noout -dates`

If `$VOLUME_NAME` isn't set in your shell, hardcode it: Replace `$VOLUME_NAME` with `hub_cert-volume` (or your exact name).

This keeps things simple—no scripts or vars needed. Once copied, proceed to step 4 (temp container to nuke old leaves). Hit me with any output/errors if it barfs!
